stringAttributes.stringValue: This column specifies the minimum salary offered for a particular job title within the HR department. Data analysts can use this to understand salary bands and compensation ranges.
Minimum salary for a job title.
This column specifies the maximum salary offered for a particular job title within the HR department. Data analysts can use this to understand salary bands and compensation ranges.
Maximum salary for a job title
Represents the full name of the country where the employee is located. Ideal for geographical analysis and reporting.
Unique identifier for the department an employee is assigned to. Useful for linking employee records to departmental data.

Department id where employee works; foreign key to department_id
column of the departments table
Contains country data including IDs, regions, and names. Ideal for filtering, aggregating, and joining data by geographical location.
country table. Contains 25 rows. References with locations table.

Consolidated employee data for HR analytics, offering insights into workforce demographics, organizational structure, compensation (salary, commission), and geographical distribution. Essential for strategic HR planning and performance evaluations.
Unique identifier for the employee's physical work location. Useful for analyzing geographic distribution of the workforce or linking to location-specific data.

Comprehensive employee records for HR analytics. Data analysts can use this table for workforce demographics, compensation analysis (SALARY, COMMISSION_PCT), organizational structure mapping (MANAGER_ID, DEPARTMENT_ID), and tracking employee tenure (HIRE_DATE). A foundational table for human capital insights.

employees table. Contains 107 rows. References with departments,
jobs, job_history tables. Contains a self reference.
Unique identifier for each country, useful for joining with other tables containing country-specific data.
The date when the employee began their employment. Critical for tenure analysis, onboarding trends, and cohort studies.
Date when the employee started on this job. A not null column.
The official name of the country, enabling human-readable identification and filtering.
This column serves as the unique identifier for each job record in the HR department. Data analysts can use this key for joining with other tables or for counting distinct job roles.
The unique identifier of the employee's direct manager. Essential for building organizational hierarchies, analyzing reporting structures, and understanding team dynamics.
Indicates the specific job title held by the employee. Useful for analyzing roles, responsibilities, and career paths within the organization.
The unique name assigned to each department, useful for categorizing and reporting by department name.

A not null column that shows name of a department. Administration,
Marketing, Purchasing, Human Resources, Shipping, IT, Executive, Public
Relations, Sales, Finance, and Accounting.
The employee's current salary. Key for compensation analysis, identifying salary trends, evaluating pay equity, and performing budget forecasting.

Contains geographical region lookups (`REGION_ID`, `REGION_NAME`) for HR data analysis. Data Analysts use it to segment HR metrics, identify geographical trends, and filter reports by region, supporting workforce planning.
The state or province where the employee's location is situated. Useful for regional breakdown of HR data, demographic analysis, and compliance reporting by region.
The primary identifier for each department, crucial for linking department information across different tables and for unique department identification.
Primary key column of departments table.
Identifies the unique department associated with a specific job history record for an employee, useful for analyzing departmental movement or tenure.
Department id in which the employee worked in the past; foreign key to deparment_id column in the departments table
Specifies the name of the department to which the employee is assigned. Essential for departmental performance analysis, resource allocation, and organizational structuring.
The city where the HR location is situated.

A not null column that shows city where an office, warehouse, or
production site of a company is located.

The percentage of sales commission applicable to the employee's salary. Can be null if the employee does not receive commission. Essential for calculating total compensation and incentive-based earnings.

Commission percentage of the employee; Only employees in sales
department elgible for commission percentage
The professional email address of the employee.
A unique identifier assigned to each employee. Use this key for linking employee-specific data across various datasets and for individual employee tracking.
Provides employee job history to analyze career progression, transitions, tenure, and employment patterns. Useful for workforce analytics and historical reporting.

Table that stores job history of the employees. If an employee
changes departments within the job or changes jobs within the department,
new rows get inserted into this table with old job information of the
employee. Contains a complex primary key: employee_id+start_date.
Contains 25 rows. References with jobs, employees, and departments tables.
The unique identifier for each employee in the HR system. This serves as the primary key for the EMPLOYEES table.
A foreign key linking to the 'LOCATION_ID' in the Locations table, indicating the physical location where the department is situated. Useful for geographical analysis of departments.
Location id where a department is located. Foreign key to location_id column of locations table.
This column contains the official title or name of the job role within the HR department. Data analysts can use this for categorizing, grouping, and filtering job-related data.
A not null column that shows job title, e.g. AD_VP, FI_ACCOUNTANT
The name of the broader geographical region an employee belongs to. Enables high-level regional analysis, comparing performance or demographics across major regions.

The conclusion date for a particular job or departmental assignment within an employee's job history, crucial for calculating tenure, analyzing historical employment periods, or identifying transitions.

Last day of the employee in this job role. A not null column. Must be
greater than the start_date of the job_history table.
(enforced by constraint jhist_date_interval)

The name of the geographical region. This column provides the textual identifier for different global areas, allowing for analysis and categorization of HR data by region (e.g., 'Europe', 'Americas').

Represents the current base salary for each employee. This column is crucial for compensation analysis, payroll processing, and understanding the financial implications of human resources. Data analysts can utilize this field to calculate average salaries, analyze salary distributions, identify pay equity gaps, and model compensation strategies within the organization.

Monthly salary of the employee. Must be greater
than zero (enforced by constraint emp_salary_min)
The state or province of the HR location.

State or Province where an office, warehouse, or production site of a
company is located.
A foreign key identifying the employee who manages the department, linking to the 'EMPLOYEE_ID' in the Employees table. Essential for organizational structure analysis and manager-specific reporting.
Manager_id of a department. Foreign key to employee_id column of employees table. The manager_id column of the employee table references this column.
The primary contact phone number for the employee.
Phone number of the employee; includes country code and area code
A unique identifier for each employee, serving as the primary key to link job history records back to individual employee profiles for comprehensive analysis across various HR datasets.

A not null column in the complex primary key employee_id+start_date.
Foreign key to employee_id column of the employee table
Contains the first name of the employee. Can be used for identification and personalization in reports, often combined with the last name.

The commencement date for a specific job or departmental assignment within an employee's job history, essential for calculating durations, analyzing employment trends, and tracking career progression.

A not null column in the complex primary key employee_id+start_date.
Must be less than the end_date of the job_history table. (enforced by
constraint jhist_date_interval)
The first name of the employee.
First name of the employee. A not null column.
A unique identifier for the job role. Useful for linking to detailed job descriptions, salary bands, and job-specific metrics.
The employee's last name. Primarily used for identification and filtering, useful when combined with first name or employee ID for personnel lookup and reporting.

Unique identifier for each geographical region. This column serves as the primary key for the REGIONS table, enabling efficient data retrieval and joins with other tables (e.g., LOCATIONS) to link employees or departments to their respective regions.
The postal or zip code for the HR location.

Postal code of the location of an office, warehouse, or production site
of a company.

Contains essential data on organizational departments for Data Analysts. Use it to analyze structures, categorize employees, and report department metrics. Key fields: DEPARTMENT_ID (unique ID), DEPARTMENT_NAME (categorization), MANAGER_ID (manager hierarchy), LOCATION_ID (department location).

Departments table that shows details of departments where employees
work. Contains 27 rows; references with locations, employees, and job_history tables.
Details HR job roles: ID, title, and salary ranges. Analysts can use it for compensation analysis, salary band understanding, and job classification.

jobs table with job titles and salary ranges. Contains 19 rows.
References with employees and job_history table.
Foreign key linking to the Countries table, indicating the country of the HR location.

Country where an office, warehouse, or production site of a company is
located. Foreign key to country_id column of the countries table.
Identifier for the region to which the country belongs, enabling aggregation and analysis by geographical region.
Region ID for the country. Foreign key to region_id column in the departments table.
Unique identifier for the job role or title held by the employee. Useful for analyzing job distribution, salary ranges per role, and career paths.

Current job of the employee; foreign key to job_id column of the
jobs table. A not null column.
The Employee ID of the manager to whom this employee reports. Enables hierarchical reporting analysis and organizational structure mapping.

Manager id of the employee; has same domain as manager_id in
departments table. Foreign key to employee_id column of employees table.
(useful for reflexive joins and CONNECT BY query)
Represents the percentage of commission an employee earns. Crucial for calculating total compensation and analyzing incentive structures.
Indicates the city where the employee is located or works. Valuable for regional analysis, workforce distribution, and localized HR initiatives.
A unique identifier for the department. Use this key to join employee records with departmental details for comprehensive organizational analysis.
Contains geographical details for HR locations (address, city, state, country). Facilitates regional HR metric analysis, trend identification, and geographical segmentation for reporting.

Locations table that contains specific address of a specific office,
warehouse, and/or production site of a company. Does not store addresses /
locations of customers. Contains 23 rows; references with the
departments and countries tables.
A unique identifier for the country. Use this key to link employee data to geographical information and perform country-specific analysis.
The physical street address of the HR location.

Street address of an office, warehouse, or production site of a company.
Contains building number and street name
Unique identifier for each HR location, serving as the primary key for this table.
The last name of the employee.
Last name of the employee. A not null column.
A unique identifier for the specific job role an employee held during a particular period within their job history, enabling analysis of job transitions, career paths, and job-specific tenure.

Job role in which the employee worked in the past; foreign key to
job_id column in the jobs table. A not null column.
